subSubSection.paragraph:
Terminalia (
Figs 15–18
). Cerci yellowish; fused to epandrium (but suture distinct), broadly concave and flattened medially, strongly prolonged anteriorly, forming small subglobular window-like space subapically (dorsal view), without pair of subepandrial lobes beneath; apical part of cercus (before epandrium) short, extended only to tergite 6, subtriangular viewed laterally, rounded apically, covered with dark setulae; posterior part of cercus broadly digitiform, rounded apically, only slightly extended beyond epandrium, with numerous dark spinule-like setulae ventrally. Epandrium usually brownish, sometimes yellowish or reddish brown, faintly greyish pruinescent, mostly with short dark fine setae longer on posterior projection; rather subglobular (lateral view), with short, rounded apically projection on lower part posteriorly. Hypandrium yellowish, subtriangular (ventral view), entirely sclerotized, bare; gonocoxal apodeme directed posteriorly, large, broadened apically. Phallus (
Fig. 18
) yellowish; short, mostly hidden (lateral view); gently arched, broad on about basal half, becoming evenly slenderer beyond epandrial projection; with two minute lateral “spinules” on apical part. Ejaculatory apodeme extended far beyond basal curvature of phallus, with narrow lateral wings and very broad vertical wing.
